<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Volvo chairman confident of allaying merger fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GOTHENBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR PEHR Gyllenhammar, the chairman of Volvo, insisted yesterday that the
chances were 'very good' of overcoming shareholder resistance to the
proposed merger of the Swedish group's car and truck operations with
France's Renault.
He said he took seriously the criticism in Sweden of his role in the affair.
He intends to stay on as chairman and retain his designated role as head of
the supervisory board of the merged company until it has achieved 'a
successful departure'.
One of Mr Gyllenhammar's toughest critics, the small shareholders'
association Aktiespararna, yesterday called on Volvo to drop the merger
plan. Its opposition was instrumental in forcing Volvo's decision last week
to postpone until December 7 a vote on the deal by its shareholders.
But Mr Gyllenhammar said, in an interview with the Financial Times, that the
company was optimistic about overcoming shareholder objections, which focus
on the lack of information on the value of the merger, the timetable for
Renault's privatisation and the French government's plans to hold a golden
share in the merged company.
'We find very little opposition to the industrial logic. We find very few
who don't believe we can make more money for shareholders together than
separately. If we can address these other concerns - give more
clarification, perhaps get positive news on privatisation - then we think
the chance is very good.'
Mr Gyllenhammar said Volvo was seeking help from Paris on the golden share
matter, in spite of French insistence that it is non-negotiable. Swedish
shareholders are alarmed that the terms could mean Volvo being forced to
lower its proposed 35 per cent share in the merged company to 20 per cent.
'We are trying to get an interpretation or assurances that it would only be
applied under certain circumstances.'
The Volvo chief, who has headed the company for 22 years, cheerfully
admitted that 'many people dislike me'. He has said he will drop all
executive roles at Volvo from next year, but he was unhesitating in saying
he wanted to stay on as chairman.
Background, Page 27
</TEXT>
