<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Exchange acts to curb price-sensitive leaks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE London Stock Exchange yesterday issued proposed guidance intended to
curb selective leaking of price-sensitive information which could give rise
to insider dealing.
However, the guidance stops short of defining price-sensitive information or
requiring quarterly financial reporting, measures sought by investor groups.
Requirements for unaudited quarterly reporting were also supported by
members of the exchange's own Large Companies Advisory Committee,
particularly those which are quoted in the US and have coped with quarterly
reporting there.
The guidance is the result of an initiative launched in late summer, in
conjunction with the 100 Group of Finance Directors as well as shareholder
and analyst associations.
That move followed the stock exchange's first ever censure of a traded
company, LIG, the world's leading branded condom maker, for telling selected
analysts of its financial condition, and concerns about insider dealing
rules in the government's new criminal justice bill.
Mr Martin Hall, director of policy at the stock exchange, said the committee
rejected quarterly reporting because too many changes in accounting policy
were pending. 'There is a feeling that requiring quarterly reporting would
be the straw that broke the camel's back.'
However, the guidance, which will be adopted formally early next year after
consultation, does go some way towards helping companies decide when they
need to make a public announcement and urges them to issue more of them. For
instance, it encourages companies to issue unaudited quarterly reports or to
make a statement about trading conditions immediately after the close of the
reporting period.
It also reminds companies that there is no such thing as a 'close period'
immediately prior to publication of profits which prevents the dissemination
of price-sensitive information. The close period merely limits the time in
which directors may deal in their own company shares.
The guidance also reminds directors they may not leak price-sensitive
information to Sunday newspaper journalists - often used to lessen the
impact on share prices of negative or controversial information. Exchange
rules require that information must also be distributed simultaneously to
two wire services and two national newspapers.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
