<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / BBC fee to rise in line with inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has granted the BBC a licence fee increase in line with
inflation until the corporation's present charter runs out at the end of
1996, Raymond Snoddy writes.
The announcement by Mr Peter Brooke, national heritage secretary, was
influenced by a report on BBC efficiency by consultants Touche Ross. The
consultants found that the BBC had pursued opportunities to make savings and
efficiency improvements 'in a rigorous and effective' manner.
Touche Ross did, however, offer the government a number of licence fee
options, including the option for a fee increase below the rise in retail
prices for two of the three years involved.
Mr Brooke said the settlement would enable the corporation to channel
savings into programmes 'and over the next three years allow the BBC
steadily to reduce and largely eliminate its annual borrowing'.
The decision was welcomed by Mr John Birt, BBC director-general.
As a result the colour television licence will rise by 1.8 per cent from
April 1 next year, from Pounds 83 to Pounds 84.50.
