<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Labour alarmed at lag in exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXPORTERS ARE losing out to companies based in other European Community
states in the race to establish markets in the former communist countries of
eastern Europe, according to figures produced for the Labour party by the
House of Commons library.
Labour said Germany, Italy and France exported substantially more than the
UK to eastern Europe last year. German exports to Poland, the Czech and
Slovak republics Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria and the former Soviet Union
amounted to Dollars 23.9bn compared with the UK figure of Dollars 2.7bn.
France achieved total sales of Dollars 4.7bn and Italy Dollars 6.4bn. The
Netherlands, with a population of just 15m, sold goods and services worth
Dollars 2.69bn.
The figures also show that British trade with eastern Europe is increasing
more slowly than that of other EC countries.
UK sales last year were 49 per cent higher than in 1990, just after the fall
of the Berlin Wall. German exports were up by 65 per cent, and Italian
exports by 51 per cent. Dutch exports were up by 76 per cent.
Ms Joyce Quin, responsible for Europe in Labour's foreign affairs team, who
obtained the figures, said urgent action was needed to make sure that
Britain obtained a larger share of long-term export opportunities in eastern
Europe.
'The problem is that the countries that get most involved in eastern Europe
in the early days are the ones most likely to win through on a long-term
basis,' she said.
'The government have not got a sufficiently co-ordinated effort going across
British industry to maximise the opportunities in these countries. Ministers
need to talk urgently to the CBI, the chambers of commerce and trade
organisations to make sure everyone understands the importance of building
up this trade.'
The government also seems worried about the trends. Mr David
Heathcoat-Amory, Foreign Office minister, admitted during Commons questions
this week that Britain's export performance to central and eastern Europe
'must, indeed, be improved'.
</TEXT>
