<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Charities' funding code to be examined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CODE of practice for government departments funding the voluntary sector
'merits serious consideration', Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, said
yesterday.
Such a code was recommended in a report resulting from discussions between
charity representatives and government departments.
The report, published by three charity umbrella bodies, warned that the
government should not place extra demands on the voluntary sector without
providing adequate resources.
The proposed code would cover such matters as the time-scale of grants, the
need to support voluntary organisations' staff training and development, and
the importance of contributing to central overheads as well as funding
specific projects.
Mr Howard told the Charities Aid Foundation conference in London yesterday
that he would ask the government's Ministerial Group on the Voluntary Sector
to examine the possibility of a code when it meets later this month.
Controversy erupted last month over another report, by three former advisers
to the Home Office Voluntary Services Unit, which recommended that charities
should lose tax relief now that many receive public funds to deliver
services. Mr John Major, the prime minister, moved quickly to stress that
tax relief would be retained, and Mr Howard yesterday distanced the
government further from the report.
A widening income gap between the biggest charities and others is revealed
in the latest edition of CAF's Charity Trends, published yesterday.
The top 200 fundraising charities increased their total income by 4 per cent
in real terms, and expenditure rose by a similar amount. But income of the
next 200 largest charities fell by 9 by cent, forcing them to cut
expenditure by about 8 per cent. Total income of the top 400 charities was
Pounds 2.8bn in 1991-92 - an annual rise of only 1 per cent, compared with
an 8 per cent increase the previous year.
