<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Lilley heads off move to cut child benefit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, has successfully resisted a
move by the Treasury to restrict child benefit to those with earnings below
the national average of Pounds 16,000 a year.
The cabinet approved yesterday the main Whitehall budgets for the next three
years, and Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, underlined his determination
to limit the cost of the compensation package for value added tax on
domestic fuel.
In his last appearance before the November 30 Budget at Commons questions,
Mr Clarke said the proposed package of measures to help the poor and elderly
with higher fuel bills would offer 'some' help to 'some' people.
Mr Clarke stressed repeatedly that the impact on heating costs of the
planned imposition of VAT would be less than feared. He told MPs: 'I would
point out there has been such a fall in gas and electricity prices during
the 1980s that even with the tax imposed in full, fuel bills will be no
higher than they were 10 years ago.'
His comments came as the prime minister's office confirmed that the size and
scope of the compensation package remains the subject of a fierce struggle
between Mr Clarke and Mr Lilley. They also coincided with a renewed attack
by Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor, on the government's refusal to
make deeper cuts in public spending.
Mr Lamont said that present policies would 'never' achieve his goal of
reducing the proportion of national income spent by government from more
than 45 per cent to less than 40 per cent.
Speaking at a London conference, the Mr Lamont added that the government
should raise health service charges and cut state contributions to social
insurance.
Downing Street said if the differences remain unresolved the dispute over
compensation for VAT on fuel could go to full cabinet before the Budget.
The size of the compensation package will depend also on whether the
chancellor decided to introduce the new tax at the full 17.5 per cent next
April rather than at 8 per cent as presently planned.
Friends of Mr Lilley said he had fought off a demand from Mr Michael
Portillo, the chief secretary to the Treasury, to 'means-test' universal
child benefit by imposing a cut-off point at the level of average earnings.
Mr Lilley had argued that the Treasury scheme was arbitrary and impractical
and broke the Conservatives' pledge in last year's general election
manifesto to protect child benefit.
</TEXT>
