<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / More executives get bonuses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BONUS SCHEMES for senior executives have become the norm for large
companies, even though only 8 per cent had them in 1979, according to a
survey.
The survey by Incomes Data Services found that few schemes were in the
public sector. The Royal Mail was the only public body to have a bonus
scheme. Its scheme covers 1,200 senior managers and 11,000 middle managers.
British Rail abandoned an attempt to introduce a bonus scheme for senior
managers in 1990.
The study says that bonuses in the private sector tended to be paid on top
of normal salaries although some companies were paying lower salaries.
It also found that some companies were allowing bonus payments to count
towards pensions.
Many companies placed ceilings on bonus payments - for example, British Gas
limited bonuses in a range from 18 per cent of salary for most senior
managers to 37.5 per cent for the chairman and chief executive.
In spite of rises such as the Pounds 1.1m bonus paid to Sir Ian MacLauren,
the chairman of Tesco, in 1990, the report found British bonuses lagging
behind US counterparts such as Toys R Us which last year paid Mr Charles
Lazarus, its chief executive Dollars 6.71m on top of his annual salary of
Dollars 315,000.
IDS surveyed 18 companies and drew information from other corporate surveys.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8741 Management Services.
</IN>
