<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Power given to the regions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE ARE two main elements to yesterday's announcement on restructuring
regional aid - the pooling of the resources of a number of government
departments in a single budget and the creation of a new administrative
structure for parcelling out grants to the English regions.
Six government departments - the Home Office and the departments of trade
and industry, environment, education, employment and transport - will pool
their separate regional aid programmes. Transport will not put any resources
into the pool, but will draw from it.
Some 20 regional development programmes will come under the control of a new
cabinet committee from April next year. It will have a budget of about
Pounds 1.4bn.
But a key element of the reforms will be the creation of 10 regional offices
to administer the aid. Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, said the
existing network of government regional offices would be merged and the area
offices would administer the new single budget and all other departmental
programmes.
Each office will be headed by a senior regional director who will be
responsible for the expenditure programme in their area, providing 'a more
comprehensive and accessible service' to local people.
Mr Gummer said the reform would make government 'more accessible and
responsive'. It would ensure that priorities were set locally and give local
people more influence over spending.
The reform met with scepticism from opposition MPs, who feared it may mask
big cuts in regional development grants in the unified Budget later this
month.
'As the packages get even glossier the money gets ever smaller,' said Mr
Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary.
Mr Gummer also launched an invitation to civic and business leaders in
London, Birmingham and Manchester to define what practical steps they want
to take on urban regeneration.
Ministers were particularly impressed by the way that Manchester's bid for
the Olympics in 2000 created new alliances between business, community
groups and the local authorities to improve the city.
The Corporation of London yesterday welcomed the initiative.
