<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Leyland Daf announces Pounds 30m modernisation plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEYLAND Daf Vans is operating profitably nine months after its management
buy-out from administrative receivership. It will be able to fund a Pounds
30m product modernisation programme from earnings, Mr Allan Amey, chief
executive, said yesterday.
Gradual recovery in the UK commercial vehicle market and the revival of
exports to continental Europe has put the Birmingham-based company on course
to achieve its output target of 12,000 units and a Pounds 150m turnover next
year, said Mr Amey. This compares with 5,000 vehicles built since the
buy-out in April.
Until February the company had been part of the Anglo-Dutch Daf commercial
vehicles group, which absorbed the formerly UK state-owned Leyland Vehicles
in 1987. The group collapsed at the beginning of this year.
Mr Amey, who projected output of a further 2,000 vans between now and the
end of the year, said the company could operate profitably at a volume of
10,000 units a year, including provision for the Pounds 30m product
programme, which is to be completed within the next two to three years. He
said the company had signed a contract with design consultancy Hawtal
Whiting to update the existing 200 and 400 model van ranges.
The company is discussing the revival of sales through some Daf dealers in
continental Europe, following the rescue of the Dutch truckmaker. Export
sales should reach 2,000-3,000 next year.
The company also plans a substantial restructuring of its operations to more
than halve the number of its component suppliers to fewer than 200.
Mr Amey was speaking as Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders
statistics showed that the UK market for panel vans, the sector in which the
company competes, jumped by about 18 per cent in October compared with the
same month a year ago.
</TEXT>
