<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Standards board retreats on reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOARD of the British Standards Institution suffered a surprising and
humiliating setback yesterday when it was forced to withdraw proposals for
sweeping changes to its constitution.
Strong resistance from BSI members at the organisation's annual meeting
forced Lord Keith, the president, to defer for at least three months
proposals to increase directors' fees and strengthen the board's powers. The
institution, which is responsible for writing standards used by industry,
said it needed three months of communication with its 29,000 members -
companies and individuals who subscribe for its services - before it could
put the proposals to them again.
This setback comes at an embarrassing time for the organisation, which is
the subject of a government review. The Department of Trade and Industry is
looking at whether it should continue to receive a government subsidy.
The institution attempted to put on a brave face, saying the problems had
arisen because of misunderstandings by its members.
But Mr Michael Sanderson, former chief executive and a critic of the
changes, said the move represented a defeat for the board unprecedented in
the organisation's 93-year history.
The annual meeting is normally a quiet affair which attracts a handful of
members and lasts only a few minutes. Yesterday it was attended by 46 voting
members and lasted nearly two hours. It was marked by long wrangles over
procedures and tough questioning of the board.
The first proposal to run into difficulties involved setting new limits to
fees which could be paid to directors. Lord Keith proposed doubling
directors' fees to Pounds 15,000 a year and the chairman's fee to Pounds
50,000.
Members then objected to a series of far-reaching changes in the
organisation's charter and by-laws. These would have strengthened the
board's powers and given it the right to make additional payments to
directors for work done beyond the normal scope of their duties.
'There was quite a full discussion but it was very clear there were
misunderstandings over what was being proposed,' said Mr Derek Prior,
communications manager.
None of the proposals were put to the vote - all were deferred pending the
consultation exercise.
Speaking before yesterday's meeting Mr Vivian Thomas, BSI chairman, said
changes to the constitution were necessary for effective decision making and
to bring its fee structure more closely into line with general market rates.
As well as organising the writing of British standards, the institution
provides testing facilities for industry. It made a pre-tax profit of Pounds
4.7m in the year ended March 1993.
</TEXT>
<XX>
