<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Squatters face earlier eviction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT sought yesterday to buttress its tougher line on law and
order by unveiling measures to strengthen legislation against 'squatting'.
In a move welcomed by shopowners but condemned by organisations representing
the homeless, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, said the legislation
would allow rapid eviction of unauthorised occupants of domestic and
commercial properties.
The legislation, expected to form part of the forthcoming Criminal Justice
Bill, would replace lengthy court procedures to secure evictions with
provision for owners and occupiers to secure immediate court orders against
squatters. There would be no need for the squatters to be present or
represented in court.
Those who refused to respond to such orders within 24 hours would be liable
to arrest and to be charged with a criminal offence. At present property
owners frequently face lengthy civil proceedings to regain possession.
Mr Howard expects local authorities and high street retail chains to make
most use of the procedures.
But law changes will also answer the frequent complaint at Conservative
party conferences about homeowners returning from holidays or business trips
to find their houses occupied by squatters. The Law Society, which
represents solicitors in England and Wales, warned that the new possession
procedures were open to abuse, with occupiers and tenants only able to
challenge proceedings after they had been evicted.
It said there was no need to create a new criminal offence or streamline
court procedures. The existing system caused delays because county courts
had insufficient resources.
</TEXT>
