<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Workshare idea splits France
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French Senate is to vote today on an experimental state aid plan for
companies that reduce regular working hours in order to take on more
employees.
The controversial plan gained surprise support this week from Mr Michel
Giraud, the labour minister, despite the divisions it has caused in the
government and in parliament. If the plan wins approval, it will return to
the National Assembly which last month rejected a similar amendment calling
for a conditional reduction from 39 to 32 hours in the legal working week in
France.
The idea of spreading available work around more people was first canvassed
by a number of Socialist leaders in last March's elections.
Mr Giraud's offer this week to exempt companies from some social welfare
charges for three years is conditional on managers agreeing to reduce their
working week by at least 15 per cent and increase their workforce by 10 per
cent, and on employees agreeing to take a pay cut.
The work-share plan cuts right across party lines. It has drawn opposition
from economic liberals like Mr Alain Madelin, minister responsible for small
business and Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing, leader of the UDF party in the
government coalition, who argue that it is just a way of 'sharing
unemployment', as well as left-wing Socialists and Communists who want the
working week cut from a maximum 39 hours to 35, without any compensating pay
cut.
But it has backing from Mr Michel Rocard, the Socialist leader, President
Mitterrand, and growing support from within the RPR Gaullist party.
</TEXT>
