<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Water regulator pledges to halt price escalation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR IAN BYATT, the water industry regulator, promised yesterday to 'get
customers off the endless price escalator' as he laid out plans for next
year's review of water prices.
His pledge, in a long-awaited consultation document, was welcomed by
consumer bodies which have complained about rising water bills and salary
increases among water company executives since privatisation. But it drew a
guarded response from the water industry and hit share prices.
Mr Byatt indicated that he planned to cut the rate of return water companies
have been allowed to earn since their privatisation in 1989. This had been
set at a deliberately high level to attract new investors, he said. Now, he
added, the risks were lower, and companies should fund future improvements
through greater efficiency or higher borrowing, rather than higher prices.
The only excuse for price rises after the new formula came into effect in
1995, he said, would be investments needed to meet higher water quality
standards, mainly from the European Community. But there would be some
flexibility based on each company's circumstances.
Mr Byatt pointed out that he did not have to agree the new 10-year price
formula with the water companies, but if they objected they could appeal to
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission. The details will be announced next
July.
'For customers, the most important message is that the rapid increase in
water prices above the rate of inflation can be moderated. I believe that it
was necessary to have had an in-crease in water prices. But customers have
become increasingly concerned at continuing in-creases above the rate of
inflation,' he said.
He expected water companies in the next 10 years to provide existing service
standards at prices 'below today's level in real terms'.
Stock market reaction was mixed. Analysts said tougher rates of return could
hit companies with large investment plans, but they drew comfort from the
fact that Mr Byatt also said he wanted to avoid disruptions. Most water
shares fell.
The Water Services Association said it shared Mr Byatt's concern about
unnecessary real rises in water bills, but added: 'It is particularly
important new investment which has to be undertaken is properly
remunerated.'
Mr Jim Gardner, chairman of the Ofwat National Customer Council, said: 'We
fully support the director-general's wish to 'stop the escalator'.'
Regulator plans fair deal for customers, Page 10
Editorial Comment, Page 19
Lex, Page 20
London stocks, Page 42
