<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Contracting out saves civil service only Pounds 100m:
Market-testing brings smaller than expected drop in costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAVINGS from contracting out civil service work have been much smaller than
expected when the market-testing programme was launched 18 months ago.
In a Commons statement, Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister,
said that market-testing - which puts civil service work out to competitive
tender - had so far produced savings of about Pounds 100m.
This compares with the Pounds 375m which would have been saved if the
programme had achieved its targets. Savings are running at 14 per cent of
the value of the work, compared with the 25 per cent figure predicted at the
launch.
Tendering has been completed on just Pounds 700m of work, less than half the
Pounds 1.5bn target set for the end of September.
Mr Waldegrave said further work worth Pounds 300m and currently carried out
by 35,000 civil servants, would be market-tested in the coming year. Next
year's programme includes many items not completed in the first round.
A 'substantial further tranche' of the first year's programme would be
completed shortly, he said, including the Pounds 250m contract for managing
the Inland Revenue's computers.
Around 10,000 civil service jobs would go as a result of the first year's
market-testing, Mr Waldegrave said. Most would be redeployed to other civil
service work, while some would be transferring to companies which had won
contracts.
Market-testing has been dogged by delays, particularly over the employment
rights of staff whose jobs are contracted out to the private sector.
Contractors have also accused the civil service of dragging its feet and
failing to realise the efficiency savings possible from contracting-out.
The results of the first round of market-testing show that the civil service
has been successful in holding on to much of the work put out to tender.
In-house teams won 57 per cent of the bids by value, and 91 of the 150
contracts awarded where there was a competition between the existing staff
and outside contractors.
In Customs &amp; Excise, just three of the 14 contracts were won by outside
contractors - all in support services. None of the VAT debt management work,
currently done by regional collection offices, went outside.
Yesterday's announcement came amid mounting complaints from private sector
companies bidding for work.
Writing in the FT yesterday, Mr Charles Cox of Hoskyns, the information
technology company, said the programme had been implemented in ways that
undermined the potential for savings. The number of private sector bidders
would diminish unless the government addressed the problems faced in winning
bids.
Another bidder said yesterday that some departments had made it very hard
for outside bidders to win. 'We've been pitching into bidding like lambs to
the slaughter,' he said.
The savings of about Pounds 100m would recur year after year, according to
Mr Waldegrave. Spectacular gains had been achieved in some parts of the
programme.
Mr Michael Meacher, Labour's Citizen's Charter spokesman, said the savings
had not come from improvements in services.
Work-to-rule, Page 12
</TEXT>
<XX>
