<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 93 / Development aid to be pooled in Pounds 1.4bn regional
package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC AID to England's regions is to be restructured in what ministers
call one of the biggest upheavals in Whitehall's relations with local
government in 14 years of Conservative rule.
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, said under the reform local people
would have more influence over spending. But the restructuring plan prompted
scepticism among opposition MPs who think it could be accompanied by heavy
development grant cuts in the Budget at the end of this month.
Under the reform, six government departments will pool their separate
regional aid programmes in areas such as housing development, education
support and business development in a single budget.
The overall programme will be administered by a new cabinet committee from
April next year, to be headed by Mr Gummer.
Until now the aid programmes have been administered by the Home Office and
the Departments of Trade and Industry, Environment, Education, Employment
and Transport.
The new committee will administer a budget of about Pounds 1.4bn in 1994-95,
some Pounds 300m less than the combined budgets of the 20 aid programmes
last year.
Mr Gummer also launched an invitation to civic and business leaders in
London, Birmingham and Manchester to define what practical steps they may
want to take in the area of urban regeneration.
Under two programmes, called City Pride and London Pride, Mr Gummer said he
planned to explore with civic and business leaders 'how they could build on
their strengths and come forward with a vision for their areas expressed in
practical terms'.
