<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / International Company News: Schroders to help Italian bank
fight bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY's first hostile takeover bid in the normally placid banking sector has
created an unexpected opportunity for Schroders, the UK merchant bank.
The bank has been appointed by the board of Banco di San Geminiano e San
Prospero, which is one of Italy's most successful regional banks. It wants
Schroders to mount a rapid defence against an unwanted takeover bid by Banca
Popolare di Verona, another sizeable regional institution.
The takeover offer, which is for only 30 per cent of the Modena-based Banco
di San Geminiano's share capital, 'seriously undervalues' the stock and goes
against the grain of Italy's new takeover laws, according to one banker
involved.
The new takeover rules permit bidders to make partial offers for an
acquisition target's capital.
However, they also require the raider to offer small shareholders the same
price as that being paid to those holding larger stakes.
Some bankers are claiming that Banca Popolare di Verona has exploited a
loophole in the new takeover legislation so it can offer a price lower than
that being paid to big shareholders.
Banco di San Geminiano is an attractive prize at a time of consolidation
among Italy's medium-sized regional banks. Net profits amounted to L60bn
(Dollars 36m) last year, while total assets were about L9,500bn. Its market
capitalisation is about L1,500bn.
Like many regional banks in northern and central Italy, it has a healthy
loan book and an attractive deposit base. Modena, home of some of Italy's
best-known specialist engineering companies, is one of the country's most
affluent cities.
In spite of Banco di San Geminiano's attempts to launch a spirited defence,
prospects for a higher offer - or the arrival of a 'white knight' to make a
counter bid - are compromised by the tight deadline for the current deal.
The offer by Banca Popolare di Verona, which claims to have already won
approval from shareholders owning 17 per cent of its target's stock, closes
at the end of this month.
</TEXT>
