<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Canadian Pizza to float with Pounds 34.5m
valuation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PRICE of 200p a share was fixed yesterday for the flotation of Canadian
Pizza valuing the pizza crust maker at Pounds 34.5m, almost Pounds 5m more
than estimated last month but Pounds 5m less than originally indicated by
the company's advisers in September.
Advisers said Mr Harry Kent, deputy chairman of the company and one of its
founders, as well as other shareholders, had been reluctant to see their
holdings diluted 'unnecessarily'.
Partly for this reason a factory the company was planning to build in
continental Europe would now be funded from cash generated internally and
debt. This accounted for most of the fall of Pounds 10m from the first
company valuation.
The Kent family, the largest shareholder, will have an 18 per cent interest
after the float, a reduction from 19.5 per cent.
The second valuation discrepancy was a function of strong institutional
demand for the shares.
Dealings in the shares are expected to start on Friday November 19.
On forecast pro-forma pre-tax profits of at least Pounds 3.35m (Pounds
2.21m) for 1993, the issue price gives a notional p/e of 15. The board
expects to recommend a final dividend of not less than 3.6p.
The total 5.9p dividend the directors would have recommended for the year
ending December 1993 would give a gross yield of 3.7 per cent. Pro-forma
earnings per share are 13.3p.
Of the 11.1m shares offered, 64 per cent of the enlarged capital, 68 per
cent are being placed firm with institutions and the balance placed subject
to clawback for the public offer for sale.
The money will be used to repay Pounds 2.5m in senior debt and redeem Pounds
11m in preference shares, including a 10 per cent premium. The float cost
Pounds 1m and the company will not be geared on quotation.
The last date for applications will be November 10, with dealing starting on
November 19.
COMMENT
The reluctance of existing shareholders to be diluted unecesssarily suggests
their awareness of the attractions of the business. However, the company's
relatively high pre-tax margins - 14.5 per cent last year going on 17 per
cent this year - makes its growing niche vulnerable to invasion by bigger
rivals. CP's biggest customers are the stingy supermarkets which account for
50 per cent of sales. But 84 per cent of the company's profits come from
crusts, a mere 12 per cent of a chilled pizza's retail selling price. The
rating, at a 14 per cent premium to the sector excluding Unilever, limits
scope for any significant initial rise.
</TEXT>
