<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Financial services help BAT shrug off cigarette price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAT Industries increased pre-tax profits by 24 per cent to Pounds 1.36bn for
the nine months to September 30. Recovery in the group's financial services
more than offset the growing impact of the US cigarette price war on tobacco
profits.
Brown &amp; Williamson, the US tobacco subsidiary, reported a 70 per cent fall
in profits during the third quarter as retailers and wholesalers reduced
orders until lower prices took effect. B &amp; W's profits for the nine months
were 50 per cent down.
Mr Martin Broughton, chief executive, said US cigarette prices were now more
stable. The price gap between premium cigarettes and economy brands had been
cut from Dollars 8 to Dollars 4 a carton.
With the prospect of a sharp rise in federal tax in October next year, Mr
Broughton said manufacturers' price increases could not be ruled out. He
also launched a sharp attack on US legislation requiring cigarette makers to
use 75 per cent US-grown tobacco in their products, calling it 'a flagrant
breach of Gatt rules'.
BAT's overall tobacco profits rose from Pounds 877m to Pounds 889m, but
declined 14 per cent if a Pounds 135m gain from an exchange of cigarette
brands with American Brands, the US tobacco and drinks group, is excluded.
Operations in Germany suffered from recession and increased smuggling,
particularly from Poland, but cigarette exports from the UK continued to
rise and higher profit contributions came from Australia, Canada, and most
African and Asian markets.
Profits from continuing financial services operations increased by Pounds
203m to Pounds 593m, with the contribution from the group's life companies
growing by 13 per cent to Pounds 229m.
Total underwriting losses on continued business at Eagle Star fell to Pounds
100m, from Pounds 244m. Both personal and commercial lines in the UK showed
substantial improvement in underwriting results. Underwriting losses from
domestic mortgage indemnity business amounted to Pounds 26m for the quarter.
The result was marred by a high level of claims from discontinued activities
at Eagle Star. Provisions on financial insurance business - mainly
commercial mortgage indemnity and agency pool business - amounted to Pounds
94m, compared with Pounds 57m at the half-way stage.
Allied Dunbar's contribution to trading profit increased by 17 per cent to
Pounds 109m, while the contribution of Farmers' grew by 8 per cent to Pounds
328m.
Earnings per share grew 56 per cent to 29.3p for the nine months.
Lex, Page 20; London SE, Page 42
</TEXT>
