<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / 'No win, no fee' law scheme attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT PLANS to allow lawyers to take cases on a 'no win, no fee' basis
came under attack yesterday from the committee appointed to advise the Lord
Chancellor on regulating the legal profession.
The public plea from the Lord Chancellor's advisory committee not to
implement the system was labelled last night as a cack-handed attempt to
push Lord Mackay into changing his mind.
There was also surprise at the timing of the committee's announcement. The
scheme's form has been known since August and Lord Mackay has made clear
that he hopes to introduce it for personal injury cases by the end of the
year.
Conditional fees - under which solicitors charge nothing if they lose but
can charge up to double their normal fee if they win - are seen by the Lord
Chancellor as a partial solution to the problem of reduced access to justice
resulting from cuts in the legal aid budget.
His original plan, which the committee says it approved of, was to allow
solicitors to charge a premium on their normal fee of just 10 per cent.
However, the profession warned the Lord Chancellor that no solicitor would
risk a case on a conditional basis for such a small reward, and Lord Mackay
agreed to increase the premium to 100 per cent.
The committee objects to the 100 per cent premium because it says there is a
danger in many personal injury cases that it could swallow up to half or
even more of the damages, which could result in serious injustice to people
of often limited means.
</TEXT>
