<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Dockers lose reinstatement case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S longest industrial tribunal case was finally resolved yesterday
when the Court of Appeal ruled against the reinstatement of 12 employees of
Tilbury Docks who lost their jobs with the Port of London Authority because
of their union work.
This overturned an industrial tribunal ruling that had ordered the
reinstatement and awarded payments and costs that would have taken
compensation, including redundancy pay for some of the workers, as high as
Pounds 100,000.
The Court of Appeal quashed the order - in effect reducing the compensation
available by between Pounds 20,000 and Pounds 30,000 for the longer-serving
highest earners.
The court ruled that it was impractical for the Port of London Authority to
re-engage the activists who were sacked in 1989.
The industrial tribunal ran for a record 197 days between 1989 and 1992
before finding that an original 19 shop stewards and activists of the TGWU
general union had been dismissed on the grounds of their trade union
activities following the abolition of the dock labour scheme.
Mr Ken Reid, TGWU regional secretary, said: 'The lads are disappointed as
you would expect.
'There is nothing worse than going 4 1/2 years with expectations high and
having them dashed by three judges who have never worked in a ship's hold in
their life.'
Since the case, he said, employers had been allowed to go back to the form
of casual labour for dock work that the unions had fought to outlaw during
the 1960s.
Overall, he said however, the case had been a victory because it had
established that employers could not dismiss staff because of their union
activities.
Only four of the original 19 have secured new jobs. 'The dockers won the
moral and legal argument over their dismissals but most of them are still
out of a job,' said Mr Reid.
He added that the Port of Tilbury, now privatised, was now recruiting casual
labour directly against the reassurances given at the time that the dock
labour scheme was abolished.
Meanwhile, two offshore drilling rig workers were yesterday awarded more
than Pounds 20,000 compensation against employers who sacked them for
refusing to take a pay cut.
The two workers were among 40 who monitored mud content in oil and gas
drills on offshore rigs around the UK for Anadrill, a subsidiary of the the
French company Schlumberger.
The two workers refused to accept basic pay reductions of 25 per cent,
believing the cuts to be in breach of their employment contracts.
Both were dismissed and took their case to industrial tribunal through their
union, the MSF technical union. One was awarded compensation of Pounds
10,820 and the other received Pounds 10,410.
Mr Roger Spiller, secretary of the MSF offshore section, said the case was
the first to challenge the interpretation of such offshore contracts.
</TEXT>
