<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Whitehall 'risks overstretching charities'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHITEHALL DEPARTMENTS have been warned not to place additional demands on
the voluntary sector without making adequate resources available, according
to a report prepared with the involvement of key government departments.
The report, to be published today, also warns that repeated changes in
government social and training policies are making the private sector and
grantmaking trusts reluctant to support social programmes.
The involvement in the drawing up of the report of the departments of
employment, education, environment and health and the Home Office gives its
findings an important status. They are likely to be considered by the
ministerial group on the voluntary sector.
Resourcing the Voluntary Sector was compiled after discussions between
charities, corporate funders and the government departments. It is the work
of three charity umbrella bodies - the Association of Charitable
Foundations, the Charities Aid Foundation and the Corporate Responsibility
Group - and will be launched at the Charities Aid Foundation conference
today.
The report says that government demands on the voluntary sector can be both
direct and indirect.
It suggests that the sector could be revolutionised by government policies
to encourage organisations to provide services under contract to public
agencies. This would also have the effect of significantly increasing funds
flowing through the sector.
However, there was a risk that contract funding might 'destroy the very
features' of the voluntary sector that led statutory funders to use it.
'These are its flexibility, choice and diversity between big and small
service providers, advocacy and watchdog functions,' the report says.
The government sets the agenda for other funders - such as private companies
and grantmaking trusts - because of its dominant position, the report says.
But companies and trusts have found dramatic shifts in government policy
'disruptive and undesirable'. Examples of such policy changes included the
Community Programme, Employment Training and Youth Training. Just as basic
government funding could attract other financial support, its withdrawal
could lead to waste and loss of funds.
Some funders had seen projects that they had supported collapse when
government money was withdrawn. As a result, the funders 'would not readily
join in partnerships to support government-funded programmes in future'.
Last month Mr John Major, the prime minister, rejected recommendations in
another report that tax relief for charities should be abolished now that
many provide services under contract to public bodies.
</TEXT>
