<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Political Notebook: Turning villains into heroes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY this government could succeed in turning errant fathers into martyrs.
That judgment on the operations of the Child Support Agency came not from an
opposition spokesman looking for an easy headline but from a sharp, if
world-weary, MP on the Conservative backbenches.
Commentators at Westminster tend to focus their attention on what they judge
to be the 'big' issues of the day. Has Mr John Major restored his grip on
the premiership? By how much will Mr Kenneth Clarke raise taxes? Has Mr
Malcolm Rifkind been forced to scrap another frigate?
But every now and then an issue unexpectedly hits MPs over the head. Their
postbags swell with complaints. Constituents queue at their weekend
surgeries with tales of hardship and demands for action.
Sometimes the preoccupations of the voters will coincide with the instincts
of the legislators: the outcry over the imposition of value added tax on
heating fuel is a good example. But more often the issue will take MPs
unawares.
The operations of the CSA, the subject this week of an investigation by the
all-party social security committee, provide the latest example. MPs of all
parties have stopped arguing about whether the government has broken this or
that promise on taxes or whether or not Mr Major is done for. Instead they
have joined forces to attack the CSA.
The agency, of course, only exists because three years ago the government,
with all-party backing, decided that absent parents - almost always fathers
 -should be made to take more responsibility for their children. There was
an easy coincidence of interest between those concerned about the poverty
endured by many single parents - almost invariably mothers - and a
government which realised that the taxpayer, through income support, was
picking up the bill for many absent fathers.
MPs should have realised, of course, there would be a fuss. As Ms Ros
Hepplewhite, the chief executive of the agency, told the committee this week
the basic intention behind the move was to achieve a significant
redistribution of income.
It was always intended that the average maintenance payment should double
from Pounds 25 per week per child to Pounds 50 per week. Mothers and the
Treasury (and mainly the latter) would be the beneficiaries. You cannot
introduce a change like that without making waves.
What few MPs realised at the time was that they were voting to give the CSA
virtually unchallengeable powers in fixing maintenance in cases where their
was no burden on the taxpayer and where parents had agreed 'clean-break'
financial settlements.
Nor did they appreciate that the crude formula used to assess maintenance
payments would take little or no account of the transfer of assets,
responsibility for children taken on through second marriages, or the
financial shock of large changes in the liabilities of absent parents.
Add to that the employment disincentive to those on low incomes facing a
huge increase in maintenance payments and the fact that most of the extra
money now being collected goes not to mothers but to the Treasury, and it is
little wonder that constituency surgeries are full of angry parents.
Ms Hepplewhite failed to offer any convincing response to the committee's
concerns. It was all up to ministers, was her most frequent response. Her
habit of answering questions in management school jargon (maintenance
payments are the CSA's 'product') did not betray much sensitivity to the
complicated world of family break-ups.
Mr Alastair Burt, social security minister, who gave evidence yesterday, was
similarly opaque. He signalled that in spite of the prime minister's pledge
of a review, his department was opposed to change.
It is true that only a small minority of the agency's cases at present
involve reopening 'clean-break' settlements. But the number will increase
sharply as the CSA spreads its net wider each year. So too will the number
of low-paid absent fathers who opt for state benefits when they see their
new maintenance bills.
In the meantime, the formula gives a father leaving his partner and children
a large financial incentive to ensure that the family home is sold and that
he maximises the cost of his new home to minimise maintenance payments.
Most MPs agree with Mr Frank Field, the select committee chairman, that the
cultural shift that the agency is designed to create - a recognition that
fatherhood bestows inescapable responsibilities - remains an essential aim.
But their postbags confirm Mr Field's judgment that it is not working
properly. Whatever Mr Burt says now, sooner or later the government will be
forced to agree.
</TEXT>
<XX>
