<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Research shows majority of defendants treated as 'economic
units'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE majority of defendants are treated as 'economic units' by their
solicitors and do not receive adequate advice or representation, research
for the Economic and Social Research Council shows, Robert Rice writes.
The study found that most defendants were encouraged by lawyers to plead
guilty to save time and costs. If they did not agree they were frequently
branded as 'nuts'.
Professor Michael McConville, the author of the research, said the main
problem was the weight of work faced by solicitors, allied to declining
levels of legal aid and a loss of values associated with adversarial
justice.
