<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / EC air policies attacked: CAA warns of threats to
competition; Blocking tactics would give rise to 'higher fares and less
choice'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Civil Aviation Authority yesterday warned of threats to competition in
the European airline industry and put forward proposals to counter delaying
and blocking tactics on 'open skies' by some European Community countries
and their national carriers.
Mr Christopher Chataway, the CAA chairman, said the EC's air transport
liberalisation policy had created the conditions for more competition but
there was a serious risk that countries would seek to undermine its
implementation.
'If the policy is not adopted in practice there could be even more
concentration, even less competition leading to higher fares and less choice
for consumers,' he warned.
Mr Clifford Paice, the CAA's head of economic regulation, added: 'The danger
is that the industry's short-term problems will lead to short-term solutions
which in turn will lead to long-term problems.'
In a document published yesterday, the CAA called for a change in EC policy
on landing and take-off slot allocation at congested airports, tougher
controls on state aid for financially troubled airlines, the application of
a more rigorous EC aviation mergers and acquisitions policy similar to the
policy applied to other industrial sectors, and stringent safeguards against
anti-competitive behaviour.
The report, which is expected to be the first of a series of documents to
maintain pressure on the EC to pursue its airline liberalisation policies,
shows that normal economy fares on EC routes in continental Europe are about
30 per cent higher than routes from the UK to the EC and domestic US routes.
It also shows that EC airline costs, with the possible exception of British
Airways, Virgin and British Midland, are significantly higher than those of
US carriers.
The report highlights the fact that most of the busiest international routes
in the EC have a congested airport at one end and that there are no more
than two airlines on most routes. 'More than 95 per cent of EC routes are
monopolies or duopolies and only 26 routes in the EC have more than two
carriers,' said Mr Paice.
The report shows that flag carriers have been forced to lower fares when a
third airline has entered a busy route.
Although the CAA is not calling for the confiscation of slots at busy
airports from dominant airlines, it is proposing a toughening of EC slot
rules which require half of all newly created slots at congested airports to
be granted to new entrants. 'We think this is not enough and too slow,' said
Mr Paice. The CAA wants all newly created, unused or otherwise available
slots to be earmarked for new competitors.
On state aid, Mr Chataway acknowledged it was unrealistic to expect it to be
completely eliminated in a European industry where only BA was a fully
privatised flag carrier. But he said a limit had to be placed on government
aid for airline restructuring which should not be allowed to finance the
acquisition of other airlines or market share.
'State aid to keep Air France afloat is OK: but financing Air France to buy
BA is not,' Mr Paice said.
Airline Competition in the Single European Market. CAA, PO Box 41,
Cheltenham, Glos, GL50 2BN. Pounds 15. Editorial Comment, Page 19 Alcazar
project, Page 21
