<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Suppliers of motor parts criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE revival of the UK motor industry is being put at risk by hundreds of
smaller component suppliers failing adequately to improve quality and
productivity standards, a Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders
conference will be warned today,
The warning will come from Professor Dan Jones, who holds the chair of motor
industry management at Cardiff Business School and is the author of the book
The Machine that Changed the World.
Prof Jones will tell the conference in Birmingham that the biggest UK
component groups have learnt from the Japanese and are trying hard to reach
world-class standards.
But he added: 'You can't have smaller component companies working to a
different set of rules when they're supplying parts which all have to be
incorporated into complete systems for the vehicle assemblers.
'The lower tiers are where we have to place the emphasis since that's where
the weaknesses lie.'
The warning to the sector reinforces one delivered by Mr George Simpson,
chairman of Rover Group, to a recent Commons trade and industry committee
inquiry into UK industrial competitiveness.
</TEXT>
