<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / MPs vote themselves a 2-phase 5.4% pay rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs in the early hours of this morning voted to award themselves a two-stage
pay rise totalling 5.4 per cent over two years.
Opening a late-night debate on MPs' pay in the House Mr Tony Newton, leader
of the Commons, defended the proposal to award MPs a pay rise larger than
the one it is trying to impose on public-sector workers.
Mr Newton confirmed that the government was proposing to offer MPs a salary
increase of 2.7 per cent next year and 2.68 per cent in 1995.
Trade union leaders and some MPs have strongly criticised the proposal. They
say the government plans to impose a much more stringent pay round on
public-sector workers, amounting to 1.5 per cent this year and a possible
freeze next year.
Mr Newton said the planned pay increase for MPs reflected wage restraint. He
recalled that MPs had received no pay increase since January 1992, despite
the rise in consumer price inflation.
He calculated that inflation had risen by 4.6 per cent since the last pay
award, and that the 2.7 per cent increase for next year would therefore make
up a little over half the amount that MPs have lost in real terms over that
period.
Miss Margaret Beckett, Labour deputy leader, gave a guarded welcome to the
proposal. She insisted that it was not an increase above the rate of
inflation, 'but rather one, properly in the circumstances, behind the rate
of inflation'.
She argued that MPs had received no increase for 18 months.
Under the proposals, the salary of an ordinary MP would rise to Pounds
31,687 next year and to Pounds 32,538 in 1995. Those receiving a
non-parliamentary salary would receive Pounds 23,854 next year and Pounds
24,495 in 1995. It is also proposed that, from 1996, increases in MPs' pay
would be annually linked to a range of civil service bands.
</TEXT>
