<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Alliance &amp; Leicester to shut administrative site
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALLIANCE &amp; Leicester, the UK's fourth largest building society, is to close
its administrative office in Hove, East Sussex, with the loss of 700 jobs to
the town over the next four years.
The withdrawal from Hove, where Alliance Building Society was based before
its merger with the Leicester in 1985, dismayed local councils. The area's
unemployment rate is above the national average.
Mr Peter White, the society's chief executive, said it had to rationalise
administrative sites, and would be concentrating its retail financial
services operation in Leicester.
He said some redundancies, almost all at Hove, would be necessary but that
it was too early to say how many. Some staff would be relocated.
The first department to leave Hove will be computer services which will move
to Leicester in the next six months.
Mr Michael Ray, director of planning at Hove Council, described the closure
as 'a devastating blow to the local economy'. Council officers are to seek a
meeting with the society. Mr Paul Bevan, economic development officer at
Brighton Council, said he was concerned because the financial services
sector was one of the main employers in the area.
The society employs about 9,500 staff in the UK, more than 1,000 of whom are
employed in sites in or near Leicester, and more than 3,000 of whom are
based in Bootle on Merseyside. Mr White emphasised that the branch network
in Sussex would not be affected by the changes, and said the measures were
needed to improve efficiency and customer service. Increased competition
within the financial services sector has put growing pressure on
institutions to reduce their administrative costs. A&amp;L's cost-income ratio
rose much more than the average for the building society sector after its
acquisition of Girobank in 1990.
</TEXT>
