<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Delay to pension reform signalled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER LILLEY, social security secretary, yesterday rejected demands from
both sides of the Commons for swift reforms to pension legislation, and
hinted that the changes could slip beyond next year. He said he would first
have to seek comment from the industry on the 1,000-page report issued by
the government's advisory panel, the Goode committee.
Mr Lilley said in a Commons statement that he would shortly be issuing
discussion papers as the basis for industry-wide consultation.
He said, however, that it would be impossible to introduce pension
legislation before the 1994-95 session at the earliest. 'We have to make
sure that what we do makes the system better and safer and does not make the
mistakes that ill-thought legislation might do,' he said.
Mr Lilley added: 'I want to listen carefully to any comments on the detail
of the committee's recommendations, not least to ensure that the burden on
business is the minimum compatible with effective regulation.'
Mr Donald Dewar, Labour spokesman on social security, welcomed the broad
contents of the Goode report but warned that Labour would want to radicalise
its recommendations.
He said the recommendation that one third of trustees should be appointed by
pension-fund members was insufficient. He called for legislation to
introduce requirements to increase pensions in line with inflation, a
proposal which the Goode committee debated at length but rejected.
'The report should be seen as a starting point, and not as the finished
product,' Mr Dewar said.
Mr Lilley also signalled that he was prepared to consider alterations to the
government's rules for schemes which contract out of the State Earnings
Related Pension Scheme and provide the alternative Guaranteed Minimum
Pension.
Industry sources have said that Department of Social Security officials have
privately indicated sympathy for requests to scrap or greatly overhaul the
minimum pension scheme, regarded as an administrative nightmare.
The Goode committee drew attention to the complexity of the contracting-out
rules and suggested that easing these might offset the burden of additional
regulation.
</TEXT>
