FT  04 NOV 93 / Call for residuary mines body rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TIM YEO, environment minister, yesterday rejected a call for a working
party to examine the environmental threat of minewater flooding and
pollution after pit closures, Chris Tighe writes.
A delegation from County Durham, including Labour MPs, county councillors
and officers, yesterday urged Mr Yeo to set up a residuary body to be
responsible for abandoned mineworkings in the post-privatisation period.
Mr Yeo said he believed a working party was not needed in view of existing
contact between the National Rivers Authority and British Coal.
Concern in County Durham over the risk of the water table rising, leading to
polluted water supplies and possible subsidence, has been heightened by the
rapid closure of local pits. This has led to fears that British Coal will
cease its pumping operations that prevent water rising into abandoned
workings.
