<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / UDM may challenge pit closure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL was yesterday threatened with a legal challenge after it
launched its pre-privatisation programme of pit closures by disclosing plans
to end mining at Calverton colliery in Nottinghamshire in a fortnight.
Leaders of the Union of Democratic Mineworkers said British Coal would
contravene the industry's modified colliery review procedure by closing the
pit on November 19 before consultations with workers would be concluded.
Calverton was one of 12 pits reprieved by the government in March.
Mr Mick Stevens, UDM general secretary in Nottinghamshire, said the pit was
financially viable and the union would fight the closure. It hoped to
persuade British Coal to keep the mine open while talks continued but would
consider a High Court challenge.
The stance of the UDM is significant because the union, which is predominant
in Nottinghamshire, is seen as more pragmatic than the National Union of
Mineworkers, the main union in the Yorkshire region, where more closure
announcements involving two to four pits are expected next week. Further
closures and mergers are expected in the next few months, to leave the
industry with about 15 pits for privatisation.
The 640 miners at Calverton will meet on Sunday to decide their next move.
Some may be tempted by British Coal's redundancy terms, which will provide
long-serving employees with up to Pounds 37,000.
British Coal said there was a precedent, at Cadeby in South Yorkshire, for
stopping production at a pit still in the review process. Calverton would be
kept in a state where it could be re-opened. Mr John Longden, British Coal
midlands director, said average production costs at Calverton were the
highest in the coalfield.
More than 22,000 workers have left the industry since last October. The
remaining 30 pits employ 19,400 miners and British Coal has 10,700 other
staff.
</TEXT>
