<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 93 / Coal fund trustees reject proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRUSTEES OF the British Coal Staff Superannuation Scheme yesterday rejected
one of the government's two proposals for administration of its pension
funds after privatisation and said the other would need significant
modifications before it could be accepted.
The scheme's trustees said their legal advisers believe that the
government's so-called Option B, which sets up a free-standing fund, 'is not
capable of satisfying the government's commitment to safeguard pensions'.
The scheme is the smaller of the two coal industry pension funds to be
affected by privatisation.
In its proposal for a free-standing scheme, the government said that members
would benefit from all of the surplus generated by better-than-expected
investment returns, but offered no protection against a shortfall. In the
worst case, this proposal could lead to a reduction in members' benefits,
the scheme's solicitors said.
However, the trustees say the government's alternative proposal will also
need further safeguards to ensure that pension promises are met. That
proposal calls for the government to act as guarantor of the scheme's
solvency, allows the government and pensioners to share in distribution of
surpluses, and sets up a 'closed scheme'. Current contributors could
participate in a new industry-wide scheme to which new employers would also
contribute.
Specifically, the trustees want the government to ensure that the practice
of increasing pensions in line with inflation is maintained.
The trustees are also calling for new legislation to codify members' rights
to index-linked pensions.
</TEXT>
